6) Stream API (Most Asked)

✅ What is Stream?
A Stream is used to process data from a collection (List/Set) in a clean way.

📌 Stream does NOT store data
✅ It only processes data.

Why use Stream?
less code
clean logic
easy filtering/mapping
no manual loops needed

Example List:
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5,6);

✅ Stream basic structure :
collection.stream()
    .intermediateOperations()
    .terminalOperation();

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 7) Intermediate Operations (Lazy)

✅ What are Intermediate Operations?
Intermediate operations are steps in between.
📌 They return a Stream again so we can chain more steps.
📌 They are lazy → they don’t execute until terminal operation is called.

Common Intermediate Operations

✅ filter() → select elements, filter returns only elements matching condition
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x % 2 == 0)

✅ map() → Used to transform data, map changes each element
list.stream()
    .map(x -> x * x)

✅ sorted() → sort
list.stream()
    .sorted()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

✅ distinct() → remove duplicates
list.stream()
    .distinct()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

✅ limit() → take first few
list.stream()
    .limit(3)
    .forEach(System.out::println);

✅ skip() → skip first few
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8) Terminal Operations (Eager)

✅ What are Terminal Operations?
They end the stream and give final result.

Common Terminal operations:
✅ forEach() → print/perform action
list.stream()
    .forEach(System.out::println);

✅ collect() → 👉 Convert stream → collection
list.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

✅ count() → count elements
long count = list.stream()
                 .count();

✅ reduce() → sum/product
✅ min(), max()

